In this article, President Obama congratulates the people of Guinea for successfully conducting their first free elections since becoming an independent state in 1958. He acknowledges the brutality and instability that threatened the country following a massacre and rape of pro-democracy demonstrators in Conakry. However, the Guinean people showed courage and determination to pull their country out of crisis and transition to civilian rule. President Obama commends the leadership of Interim President General Sékouba Konaté and the support of the international community in making these elections a success. He urges all parties in Guinea to continue choosing the rule of law and peaceful political participation over division and violence, assuring them of the United States' support.